hat it means to endure in an ecologically volatile world, Second Site provokes us to rethink long-held beliefs about the permanency of site-based art, and carries implications for how we understand artistic creation and the conservation of cultural heritage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEarthworks (Art) 0aEarthworks (Art)xConservation and restoration. 0aEarthworks (Art). 0aTime and art. 7aART / Environmental & Land Art.2bisacsh  aAlan Sonfist.  aAnnette Michelson.  aAnt Farm (group).  aAntoine de la Mothe Cadillac.  aArt criticism.  aArt history.  aAstrology.  aAt Dawn.  aAtlantic slave trade.  aBonnie Devine.  aBruce Springsteen.  aBruno Latour.  aBuckminster Fuller.  aCadillac Ranch.  aCalculation.  aCamp Ipperwash.  aChip Lord.  aClassical tradition.  aColonialism.  aConsciousness.  aConservation area (United Kingdom).  aConstruction.  aContemporary art.  aCreative work.  aCurator.  aDocumenta.  aDocumentary film.  aDonna Haraway.  aDrought.  aEarth Day.  aEcological succession.  aEcology.  aEcosystem.  aEdgar Heap of Birds.  aEnvironmental history.  aEnvironmental protection.  aEnvironmentalism.  aEphemerality.  aExplanatory model.  aFine-art photography.  aFluxus.  aFrench Colonial.  aGenocide of indigenous peoples.  aGravel road.  aGreat Basin Desert.  aGreek mythology.  aHelen Escobedo.  aIan McHarg.  aIndigenous peoples.  aIpperwash Crisis.  aJoan Jonas.  aJon.  aLand art.  aLandscape.  aLegislation.  aLocal history.  aMarcel Duchamp.  aMathias Goeritz.  aMel Bochner.  aMichael Heizer.  aMilitary exercise.  aModernity.  aNancy Holt.  aNew York City Department of Parks and Recreation.  aNorth America.  aOak Ridges Moraine.  aObsolescence.  aOld-growth forest.  aOri